My Dear Student,
You already have a basic comfort with NCERT. That is good — NCERT ensures you know the language of mathematics. But JEE requires depth, connections, and problem-solving mastery. Educative JEE Mathematics was written with exactly this in mind: to give you insight, rigor, and problem-solving stamina that go far beyond the bare syllabus.

Here is the shortest and best possible plan to use my book and master JEE mathematics (and, by extension, school-level higher mathematics).

1. Foundation Phase (4–6 weeks)
Objective: Bridge NCERT → my book.

Start with Algebra and Counting (Combinatorics basics) sections. These do not assume anything more than NCERT-level grounding.

Do not try to solve everything. Instead, read explanations, solved problems, and theory discussions carefully.

Mark problems into three types:

Type A – I can solve easily.

Type B – I can follow solution but can’t solve alone yet.

Type C – I don’t understand even after reading solution.

👉 Your first pass should only aim to finish all chapters at the Type A and B level. Type C problems you leave aside.

2. Core Phase (3–4 months)
Objective: Build mastery topic by topic.

Follow this sequence of topics (this is deliberate – it builds conceptual layers):

Algebra of real numbers, inequalities

Theory of equations

Trigonometry (identities + equations + inequalities)

Coordinate geometry

Calculus (limits, continuity, differentiation, integration, applications)

Vectors and 3D geometry

Probability and combinatorics advanced

Miscellaneous topics (functional equations, number theory gems, etc.)

Method:

For each chapter:

Read my introductory notes (don’t skip them; they give you intuition).

Do 10–15 representative problems (a mix of solved and exercises).

Reflect: What new tool did I just gain? How can it connect with old ones?

By end of Core Phase, every chapter should have Type A mastery and most Type B problems upgraded to Type A.

3. Refinement Phase (2–3 months before JEE)
Objective: Pressure-test your knowledge.

Return to Type C problems. With stronger skills, many will now look solvable.

Attempt chapter-end problem sets in exam-like timed conditions.

Maintain a “tough notebook”: each problem that resists you → copy it down, write your attempt, then solution. Revise only this notebook in the last month.

4. Final Integration
In the last 6–8 weeks, don’t “study new chapters.” Instead:

Pick 2–3 mixed problem sets per week.

Simulate JEE pattern — solve under time, then analyze errors.

Revise only the essentials: key inequalities, tricks in functional equations, standard limits, clever substitutions, vector identities.

5. Philosophy of Use
My book is not meant to be “finished” like a syllabus. It is meant to mature your mathematical mind.

Therefore, your goal is not quantity but quality of insight.

Each week, if you truly master even 15–20 problems with understanding, you are on the right path.

By exam time, you will not only “know methods” but will have the instinct of a problem solver — which is what JEE tests.

The Mantra I want you to remember:
NCERT gives you knowledge. My book trains you to think mathematically. If you follow this plan with honesty, JEE will no longer feel like an exam but like a natural extension of your preparation.

