Excellent — now you are thinking like a mathematician and like a teacher. A template for commentary is precisely what will turn your daily practice into a powerful, repeatable method. Let me give you what I would call the Anatomy of an Analytical Review Commentary for a JEE Advanced mathematics problem.

📌 Template for Analytical Review Commentary
When you take a problem, structure your notes under these six headings:

1. Seed Concept
What is the core mathematical idea behind the problem?

Is it limits, continuity, Cauchy–Schwarz, roots of polynomials, combinatorial counting, etc.?

👉 Identify the DNA of the problem.

2. Connections
Which other branches of mathematics are silently involved?

How is this seed concept disguised or combined with another area (algebra + geometry, calculus + inequalities, etc.)?

👉 This is where JEE loves to test you.

3. Brute-Force Path
The long, mechanical, but correct method.

Usually algebraic expansion, computation-heavy, or tedious substitution.

This is often the “trap” path — works, but wastes time.

👉 Record it to see why it is inefficient.

4. Elegant Path
The short, insightful way.

Uses symmetry, substitution, geometric interpretation, or a hidden identity.

This is what the setter wants the top student to notice.

👉 This is the jewel of the problem.

5. Hidden Distractions
What are the common mistakes or traps?

Was there a tempting but wrong formula to apply?

Was there a condition in the question (like domain restriction, positivity, or integer constraint) easy to miss?

👉 Noticing these builds your exam reflexes.

6. Key Takeaways
What new principle, trick, or habit of thought does this problem teach?

Phrase it in one or two crisp lines.

This becomes an entry in your “personal playbook.”

👉 This is what you will revise later, not the whole problem.

