The 6-part template you wrote — [seed concept – connections – brute path – elegant path – hidden distractions – key takeaway] — is already very good. It captures the essence of what a deep commentary must achieve: it makes the student see not just how a problem is solved, but why it is posed that way, what it reveals, and what traps it hides.

But — it can be slightly rebalanced to become the most efficient “anatomy” for JEE problem reviews. Based on my experience (both teaching and dissecting problems), here’s what I would recommend as the ideal anatomy:

🔹 Anatomy of a Good Analytical Commentary
Seed Concept(s)

Identify the core idea(s) without which the problem cannot move.

Phrase them in the simplest possible way: e.g., “This problem rests on symmetry of conics + AM–GM inequality.”

Purpose: It anchors you.

First Natural Impulse (Brute Force Path)

What would a student first try if they had no cleverness? (Write this down.)

Often this is algebraic grinding, direct substitution, or brute computation.

Purpose: To acknowledge the obvious route, and to see why it is inefficient.

Hidden Structure / Elegant Idea

The concealed key that unlocks the problem: symmetry, substitution, invariance, clever inequality, geometric transformation.

This is the aha moment JEE is testing.

Purpose: To highlight that JEE rarely rewards grinding; it rewards spotting structure.

Common Traps & Distractions

Note where a student might be misled: irrelevant identities, overcomplication, or applying the wrong theorem.

Purpose: To train yourself to avoid wasting exam time.

Connections & Generalizations

Ask: “Where else does this technique live?”

