Short answer: Yes — the commentary method works very well for physics, but it needs to be adapted.
Physics problems are solved by the same deep-thinking habits (spot the seed, resist the obvious, seek structure). But because physics models the real world, your commentary must emphasize physical picture, assumptions, approximations and sanity checks more than pure math does. Below I explain exactly why it works, how to adapt the template, and how to practise — with a worked qualitative application to a classic mechanics problem so you can feel the method in action.

1) Why the commentary approach also works for Physics
Same cognitive target: Both fields test model recognition, abstraction and insight. JEE/Olympiad physics problems hide a seed (conservation, noninertial frame trick, symmetry, clever coordinate choice) and often bait students into brute algebra. Writing a commentary trains you to see the seed and the elegant modeling move before calculating.

More emphasis on modeling: Physics adds layers — assumptions, approximations, units, and limiting behavior. The commentary method forces you to record and check these explicitly instead of glossing over them.

Fosters physical intuition: When you write why a certain frame or conservation law is the right pivot, you build an intuition library — the exact goal of HC Verma style training.

Teaches exam-useful habits: Drawing diagrams, checking limits, dimensional analysis, and estimating magnitudes — all become automatic when they’re part of your commentary checklist.

So yes — it will work, and it will be powerful — provided you tailor the template for physics.

2) A Joshi-style Physics commentary template (use this every day)
Physical setup & seed (core idea)

State the configuration and the single sentence: what is this problem really about? (e.g., constraint motion, energy exchange, center-of-mass translation, rotating frame, diffraction, thermodynamic cycle.)

Explicit assumptions & modeling choices

Friction? Rigid bodies? Point masses? Ideal springs? Quasi-static? Small-angle? State them — this is crucial in physics.

Physical picture & diagram

A clear labelled sketch (forces, directions, coordinates). Mention the convenient coordinate system and why.

First impulse / Brute calculation

The obvious approach students try (resolve all forces, write components, long algebra). Note why this is natural and what it will involve.

Elegant physical pivot (the insight)

The key modeling or conceptual move: choose the right conserved quantity, switch to center-of-mass frame, use virtual work, choose generalized coordinates / Lagrangian, use symmetry or adiabatic approximation. Provide the short derivation/steps.

Checks, limiting cases & dimensions

Test extremes (mass→0, length→0, angle→0, friction→∞), do dimensional analysis, sanity-check sign and magnitude.

Pitfalls, hidden traps & experimental intuition

What distracts students? Where do people forget reaction forces, apply conservation illegally, forget sign conventions? Note what experimental/physical intuition would reveal.

Connections & generalizations

Where else this pivot shows up (optics, EM, statistical physics). Suggest variants to practice.

Key takeaway (one-line rule or heuristic)

A sharp rule you can keep on a flashcard.

Optional: Quick numeric estimate

If constants are given, estimate order of magnitude — builds judging sense.

3) How to use the template in practice (daily routine for physics)
Daily: 1 deep physics problem → fill the full commentary (45–90 min). Re-solve after 1 week.

Twice weekly: 2–3 speed problems (force questions, kinematics numericals) under time.

Weekly review: synthesize 6 commentaries into a “Physics patterns” page: conservation tricks, typical noninertial-frame signals, standard small-angle linearizations, energy vs. force choices.

Add lab-style mental experiments: ask “if this experiment were done in reality, what would I measure?” This improves intuition for approximations.

4) Why physics needs extra checklist items (and what they are)
When you transfer the math blueprint to physics, add these recurring checks:

Units / Dimensional Analysis: Always check units of your result; helps catch algebra mistakes.

Sign conventions: Directions and sign errors are common — record them early.

Validity of conservation laws: Are there external forces/torques? Are constraints non-holonomic? If so, conservation may not apply.

Small-parameter expansions & linearization domain: If you linearize (small angle, small velocity), state the range where approximation is valid.

Energy vs. Newton choice: Choose the method that minimizes unknown constraint forces. Often energy + virtual work is much cleaner than resolving constraint forces.

