1. The core insight: seed, wrapper, pivot
Seed: one simple fundamental — a theorem, invariant, conservation law, symmetry, substitution or logical structure.

Wrapper: the problem’s surface complexity — algebraic mess, layers of calculation, unfamiliar language, intentional decoys.

Elegant pivot: a small conceptual move (change of variables, frame shift, symmetry exploitation, an invariant) that makes the seed visible and collapses complexity.

The goal of commentary-writing is narrative: show how the wrapper misleads, how you discovered (or would discover) the seed, and how the pivot yields the elegant solution — then extract a durable rule.

2. The four universals of elegance
No matter the domain, elegant solutions live in these four universals:

Invariance — something stays the same across transformations or operations.

Symmetry — balance or interchangeability which drastically reduces cases.

Substitution — rephrasing the problem in a more natural variable/coordinate/frame.

Logic (structural reduction) — exposing underlying logical skeletons (contradiction, extremal, induction).

All other useful maneuvers — analogy, extremal arguments, duality, geometric visualization — are expressions or combinations of these four.

