Preface — what this volume is for
This book trains a student to think like an examiner and solve like a mathematician. Its aim is not faster mechanical solving but the deliberate cultivation of pattern-recognition, seed-detection, and the craft of writing clear analytical commentaries. Read, practice, and write — your commentary journal is the central instrument of learning.

1. High-level Philosophy
1.1 Core insight
Every high-quality problem hides a seed (a simple fundamental idea) beneath a deceptive wrapper (algebraic mess, unusual phrasing, tempting standard methods). The solver’s craft is to find the seed and execute an elegant pivot that collapses the wrapper into a short, conceptual solution.

1.2 The four universals of elegance
All elegant moves are manifestations of these four primitives:

Invariance — something conserved or unchanged.

Symmetry — exchangeability, balance across variables or structure.

Substitution — changing viewpoint (variables, coordinates, representation).

Logic (structural reduction) — exposing skeletons via contradiction, extremal, induction.

Everything else (analogy, transformation, extremal method, etc.) is a combination or instance of these universals.

2. Anatomy: How to Analyze & Write a Commentary
2.1 The 6-part Commentary Template (Your daily stencil)
For every deep problem, write under these headings:

Seed (Problem core) — One-line identification of the core idea(s).

Brute Path / First Impulse — What a competent but uninsightful student would try first; why it's tempting.

Elegant Pivot — The key idea/substitution/invariant; present a concise solution built from it.

Pitfalls & Distractions — Common mistakes and why they fail; examiner’s traps.

Connections & Generalizations — Where does the pivot recur? Simple variants and extensions.

Key Takeaway (one line) — Distill into a flashcardable rule.

Write each section clearly; the Elegant Pivot should be short and convincing. Add a variant or a counterexample where helpful.

2.2 How to write it (practical steps)
Attempt first (20–40 min). Record your first impulse.

Read official/author commentaries or solution (carefully). Mark the pivot sentence.

Write the 6 parts in your own words. Time allocation: 60–120 min per master commentary initially.

Create 1 variant (change a parameter, change domain) and predict effect; test briefly.

Schedule revisit: re-solve the problem from scratch 2 weeks later without notes.

