5.3 Scoring philosophy (what examiners reward)
Correctness + clarity + concision. Elegant arguments often score better than long messy computations even if both are correct; examiners prefer reasoning that communicates why the step works.

6. The Mind of the Solver — developing habits
6.1 Process habits
Read slowly; rephrase in your own words.

Identify constraints and invariants immediately.

Try small numbers / examples to see shape.

Resist the direct expansion impulse for 5–10 minutes; search for a conceptual lens.

6.2 Psychological habits
Stay calm; time pressure kills insight. Practice calm problem meditation: if stuck, annotate every small attempt and step back.

Embrace failure attempts as data: record them in commentary — they often point to the pivot indirectly.

Work to increase recognition speed: target < 10–15 min to spot likely seeds on typical JEE-Advanced problems after months of practice.

