Choose the seed: pick a single strong central idea (e.g., substitution, invariant, inversion).

Design the elegant path first: construct a short, convincing solution based on seed.

Add plausible distractors: add structures that make a brute path look attractive (objects that invite standard formulas).

Build layers: include a base that tests fundamentals, then embed the twist.

Test solve: ask peers to attempt; refine to ensure the elegant path exists and is discoverable with reasonable effort.

Write marking scheme: indicate partial credit points and common wrong answers.

