Thought for 11s
Philosophy of Problem Solving — Part II: Physics
A practical, chapter-ready, and classroom-ready manual for training students to think like examiners and solve like physicists. This volume teaches the seed→elegance method applied to physics: how to spot the hidden law, choose the right model, avoid traps, write rigorous analytical commentaries, and — crucially — design good problems so students learn the examiner’s craft.

Preface — purpose & scope
This book trains students to:

detect the seed (the small physical principle or modeling choice that decides the problem),

perform an elegant pivot (frame/variable/approximation that collapses complexity),

write clear physics commentaries (assumptions, diagram, pivot, checks), and

construct realistic exam-level physics problems (so they can think like setters).

It is written for students preparing for JEE Advanced and Physics Olympiads (RMO/INPhO/IOI-style physics), and for teachers who want to adopt a commentary-driven pedagogy.

1. Core philosophy (physics edition)
1.1 The same meta-truth
Just like in mathematics, an advanced physics problem is usually hide-and-seek: the setter buries a simple physical law (seed) under layers of algebra, coordinates, or distracting computation. The solver’s job is not to grind but to recognize which law to use and in what frame/approximation.

1.2 Physics-specific universals of elegance
Four universals remain central, but with physics flavor:

Invariance / Conservation — conservation of momentum, energy, charge; invariants under transformation (Galilean/Lorentz invariance).

Symmetry — geometric/electromagnetic/temporal symmetry that kills integrals or predicts zero results.

Substitution / Frame Change — moving to center-of-mass frame, rotating frame, normal modes, or changing variables (e.g., use reduced mass).

Logic / Model Reduction — choose minimal model, state approximations explicitly, use limiting cases.

Everything else (superposition, linearization, dimensional analysis, analogy) is an expression of these.

2. The Physics Commentary — Template & How to Use It
Use this template every time you analyze a physics problem. Your commentary becomes your memory and your teaching tool.

Physics Commentary Template (fill each section)
Problem ID / Source / Date / Time spent

Seed (one-line) — the core law or modeling idea (e.g., “horizontal momentum conserved because no external horizontal force”).

Assumptions & Modeling Choices (explicit) — friction? rigid body? small-angle? quasistatic? mention and justify.

Physical Picture & Diagram — labeled sketch; define coordinates and sign conventions.

First Impulse / Brute Path — what most students try (resolve all forces, long vector algebra). Why tempting; list steps briefly.

Elegant Pivot (the insight) — frame change, conservation law, symmetry, or trick. Show the minimal derivation (equations, not paragraphs).

Checks & Limiting Cases — units, dimensions, extremes (m→0, θ→0), energy sign, sign conventions.

Pitfalls & Common Mistakes — incorrect conservation application, wrong sign, ignoring constraint forces, domain of approximation.

Connections & Generalizations — other problems where pivot works; possible experimental realization; parametric variants.

Key Takeaway (one-line) — bite-sized memory rule (to be added to SRS/Anki).

Revisit date & re-solve score — when you’ll test memory and what your target is next time.

How to use it
Attempt first (30–60 min) and write the brute path even if it fails.

Then study elegant solution(s) and annotate pivot sentence(s).

Write the commentary within 60–90 minutes the first time; update after re-solve.

Add one constructed problem (optional): change a parameter to make a variant.

3. Seed-Detection Toolkit for Physics
These are the “lenses” to run over every problem in the first 3–10 minutes.

3.1 Conservation Laws
Linear momentum (which directions), angular momentum (about which point), mechanical energy (when non-dissipative), charge, magnetic flux (in certain circuits), etc.

3.2 Frame / Coordinate Choices
Center-of-mass (CM) frame, inertial vs. non-inertial, rotating frame (Coriolis), lab frame vs moving support, normal/tangential coordinates in constrained dynamics.

3.3 Superposition / Linearity
For fields, circuits, waves; break into components that you can add.

3.4 Symmetry & Gauss / Ampere selection
If geometry has planar/spherical/cylindrical symmetry, use Gauss/Ampere. For waves, use boundary symmetry.

3.5 Dimensional & Scaling Analysis
Guess functional forms, check plausibility, identify characteristic time/length scales.

3.6 Small-Parameter & Approximations
Small-angle (sinθ≈θ), non-relativistic, weak coupling, adiabatic/fast-slow separation.

3.7 Energetics vs Force Approach
If constraints are unknown, energy methods often win; if trajectories needed, Newton’s laws may be necessary.

3.8 Kinematic Constraints
Holonomic vs non-holonomic; geometric constraint equations tie variables—simplify using constraint relations.

Run this checklist in your head: e.g., “Is momentum conserved? Could CM frame help? Is there symmetry for Gauss? Could I linearize?”

4. Grand Themes of Elegance in Physics (annotated)
These are high-frequency seeds—if you spot them, you’re near the pivot.

Conservation of Momentum — moving supports, collisions, rocket problems.

Conservation of Energy — oscillations, springs, pendula, energy exchanges.

Conservation of Angular Momentum — rotational dynamics, central force problems.

Superposition/Linearity — circuits, waves, small oscillations (normal modes).

Center-of-Mass / Reduced Mass — two-body problems simplified.

Symmetry & Gauss/Ampere — field problems where flux eigenfunctions apply.

Frame shifts & Relative Velocity — river-boat, moving platforms, Doppler.

Adiabatic / Quasi-static approximations — thermodynamics, slow vs fast processes.

Dimensional, Scaling & Similarity — pendulum period, wave scaling, Reynolds number in fluids (conceptually).

Monovariants/Invariants in iterative processes — collisions with restitution, discrete processes.

Limiting cases as sanity checks — check extreme mass limits, stiffness → infinity/zero.

5. Must-Know Physics Concepts & Techniques (compact checklists)
These are essentials students must internalize before writing deep commentaries.

5.1 Mechanics
Kinematics (translational + rotational), Newton’s laws, work–energy theorem, impulse–momentum, center-of-mass, reduced mass, small-angle approximations, Lagrangian basics (when useful), constraints and normal forces, pseudo forces in non-inertial frames.

5.2 Oscillations & Waves
SHM equations, energy partition, normal modes for coupled oscillators, wave superposition, standing wave boundary conditions, resonance basics.

5.3 Electricity & Magnetism
Coulomb’s law, Gauss’s law (symmetry cases), electric potential relations, Biot–Savart/Ampere’s law (symmetry cases), Faraday’s law & Lenz’s law, RL/RC/LC circuit time constants and phasor intuition.

5.4 Optics & Waves
Fermat’s principle, Snell’s law, interference (double slit), diffraction (qualitative), imaging by thin lenses.

5.5 Thermodynamics & Statistical
First and second laws, PV work, ideal gas basics, quasi-static processes vs irreversible, specific heat and adiabatic exponent.

5.6 Modern Physics (basic)
Photoelectric effect, basic Bohr model, relativistic energy–momentum relations (conceptual).

5.7 Mathematical Tools
Vector calculus basics, Taylor expansions, complex phasors in circuits, Laplace transforms notionally, solving linear ODEs for common setups.

