7. The Mind of the Physics Examiner — how problems are constructed
7.1 Setter’s objectives
Test modeling judgment: can candidate state assumptions and choose correct conserved quantities?

Test approximations: small-angle linearization, ignoring friction, weak coupling.

Test experimental instinct: check limiting behavior (does result make sense physically?).

Force clarity under time pressure: reward clear, minimal solutions.

7.2 Typical disguises
numeric mess designed to look solvable by brute algebra, but elegant path uses symmetry or conservation;

mixed-discipline problems (mechanics + thermodynamics + statistics) where a simple thermodynamic argument solves fastest;

hidden small parameter invites linearization but many attempt exact algebra.

8. The Art of Constructing Physics Problems (teach setters’ craft)
Construction trains students to spot traps and design wrappers.

8.1 Step-by-step recipe
Pick a seed: conservation law, symmetry, frame trick, normal mode.

Design an elegant solution first: the solution must be conceptual and short.

Create a plausible wrapper: add friction, moving support, or irrelevant parameters that tempt brute algebra.

Insert distractors: include quantities that invite wrong conservation (e.g., add gravity but obscure external horizontal force).

Test: ask peers to attempt; refine to ensure solution requires insight but is discoverable.

Write marking scheme with partial-credit suggestions for common wrong attempts.

8.2 Example construction (short)
Seed: horizontal momentum conservation.

Wrapper: block slides on wedge on frictionless surface — many try eliminate normal.

Distractor: add a small friction coefficient in part (b) to check erosion of conservation and force students to state assumptions.

9. Classroom & Curriculum Design for Physics (how to teach)
9.1 Daily habit (risk-balanced)
Morning (1–2 hrs deep): 1 deep commentary on a physics problem (60–90 min).

Afternoon (1–2 hrs speed): 6–8 short problems timed (concept checks, quick calculations).

Evening (30–60 min): SRS flashcard review of key takeaways + unit checks.

Weekly: 1 review day (re-solve 6 commentaries), peer-review of commentaries. Monthly: full-length physics mock + synthesis essay.

