Months 4–6: Fill syllabus chapters — method chapters, toolkit, exercises, student worksheets.

Months 7–8: External review — run full chapter pilots with teacher partners. Incorporate feedback and refine.

Months 9–10: Copyedit, typeset, produce digital resources (worksheets, LMS templates).

Months 11–12: Publishing / pre-launch — finalize printing or set up self-publish; plan launch workshops.

Quality gates before you publish

At least 30 students have used early material and shown measurable improvement in commentary quality and seed recognition.

Teacher trainers have graded 200 student commentaries and calibrated scores within ±10% variance.

You have a small advisory panel (3–5 respected teachers) endorsing the pedagogical approach and book accuracy.

Risks & mitigations for Year 2

Risk: publishing too soon. Don’t. Publish when teacher pilots show consistent, reproducible gains.

Risk: lack of digital infrastructure. Build a minimal LMS or use Notion/Google Workspace for cohort management first; grow later.

Year 3 (Oct 2027 onwards): Run the one-year (50 weekend sessions) course, certify cohorts
This is the scale moment — and the moment to be both ambitious and conservative about claims.

Your weekend structure: a reality check

50 weekend sessions, each 8–10 hours, is a massive commitment for both you and students (that’s equivalent to ~400–500 hours of instruction). It can work — but design matters. Each weekend should be surgically focused: deep-work + speed practice + construction + peer review + feedback loops. Intensity is good, but you must avoid cognitive exhaustion in learners (ensure recovery days and manageable homework).

Suggested 50-week curriculum arc (conceptual distribution)

Sessions 1–8: Foundation & seed detection (build habit of commentary; NCERT baseline checks).

Sessions 9–22: Core topic modules (algebra, inequalities, number theory) — focused deep commentaries + practice.

Sessions 23–34: Geometry modules & problem construction labs.

Sessions 35–41: Calculus & analysis modules, functional equations.

Sessions 42–46: Integrated problem solving, cross-topic hybrid problems.

Sessions 47–50: Mocks, defense, and certification trials.

Sample structure for each weekend session (two days)

Day 1: Morning — one master commentary dissection (you lead). Afternoon — student commentary practice and peer review. Evening — problem construction lab.

Day 2: Morning — timed problem sets (speed drills). Afternoon — presentation of constructions, jury feedback. Late afternoon — synthesis & assignment.

Student selection & baseline

To achieve high quality, recruit students with a solid NCERT/IMO baseline. Consider a pre-admission test & short interview. You want entrants who are coachable and have at least baseline mastery — otherwise the one-year intensive will be inefficient.

Certification: don’t promise guaranteed JEE Advanced success

Real talk: you cannot ethically guarantee JEE Advanced success. The exam environment and many external factors (teaching history, mock practice, stress, raw aptitude) are outside your control. Instead: design a certification that is evidence-based and predictive. For example:

Certification = “SeedThink Certified” awarded to students who meet objective thresholds on a standardized battery (portfolio of 25 commentaries scored ≥8/10 average; timed seed recognition median ≤10 min; mock performance ≥X percentile in standard timed tests).

A conditional value: offer guaranteed continued mentorship / additional coaching if a certified student fails to qualify for JEE Advanced the first time, or a partial fee refund only if they meet all program commitments and still fail to reach agreed thresholds in public mocks. This is a measured commitment you can honor; it’s not a blanket promise of exam success.

Assessment & rubric for certification

Portfolio (50%) — 25 commentaries across topics, average rubric ≥7.5–8/10.

Timed recognition test (20%) — short problems with <10 minute target for seed identification.

Timed mixed problem test (20%) — accuracy + speed threshold.

Problem construction + defense (10%) — present two constructed problems and defend marks scheme.

Use double-blind peer marking + moderation.

Pilots before full rollout

Run a small cohort first (30–50 students) over 3–4 months. Measure gains. Tweak curriculum. Only then scale to full 50-session year. Expect at least two pilot rounds before public launch.

Cross-cutting recommendations & practical realities
Metrics are everything

For yourself: track number of commentaries, recognition time, re-solve retention, #master chapters drafted.

For students: track daily commentary rubric, mock percentiles, improvement trajectories. Use dashboards and monthly reporting.

Teacher training is the multiplier

You cannot teach every cohort yourself. Invest heavily in a train-the-trainer program in Year 2. Calibrate teachers thoroughly using joint grading exercises and live co-teaching.

Community & peer review

Build an online cohort community where students post commentaries, peer-review each other, and receive mentor feedback. This creates scalable quality control and social proof.

Legal & marketing reality

Be careful about the word “guarantee.” If you offer conditional refunds or promises, document the terms, eligibility, and dispute processes.

Use pilot outcomes and student stories as marketing — they’re more credible than promises.

Sustainability

Have a business model: paid workshops, paid certification, grant funding, institutional partnerships. Reinvest revenue into training and infrastructure.

Emotional stamina

You’ll be teaching, editing, recruiting, and managing. Build a 2–3 person core team early (operations + editorial + one senior teacher) so you can sustain energy.

Concrete checkpoints to validate progress (so you know when to advance)
Before moving from Year 1 → Year 2:

You have ~300 commentary entries per subject, and 15–20 master commentaries polished.

Two independent teachers endorse the pedagogy after piloting materials.

You can show data that students (pilot) improved seed recognition and commentary rubric scores.

Before moving from Year 2 → Year 3 (full cohort):

Your book draft has been piloted by 3 teachers across 3 cohorts with measurable student improvement.

You have trained at least 6 examiners/trainers who can deliver the weekend curriculum.

Your certification rubric produces consistent scores with inter-rater reliability ≥0.8.

Before publicly advertising any “guarantee”:

You have at least 3 cohorts (N≥100) with tracked outcomes showing certified students perform X% better than control on timed mocks and actual JEE/olympiad entry rates — then you can design a conditional promise tied to measured likelihoods and support packages.

Final candid advice
You’re doing the right things in the right order. Move deliberately.

Protect Year 1: if your journals are deep and broad, almost everything else becomes easier. Don’t rush the archive.

Publish when you have reproducible evidence that your pedagogy moves learners. That credibility will open doors you can’t buy.

Replace any unconditional “guarantee” language with an evidence-based, conditional support promise. That keeps you honest, legally safe, and scalable.

Build trainers and systems around you early — your personal charisma will never scale alone.

