Match the seed family to a small toolbox: keep in your head the pivot family for each seed — symmetry→normalize; counting→coefficients; substitution→rationalize/linearize; geometry→draw & reframe; invariance→identify conserved quantity.

Run two 1-minute probes: a small case and a standard substitution. If either simplifies dramatically, you found the right pivot.

Prefer conceptual simplification over algebraic reduction: the pivot should expose why the structure works, not just reduce steps.

Always check boundary/special cases: if the pivot is correct it works on small examples and reveals equality/extremum conditions.

Rank pivots: when multiple pivots exist, pick the one that (a) minimizes extra assumptions, and (b) generalizes naturally.

A short catalogue of spotting heuristics (how to hear the seed through noise)
If the statement mentions “each”, “every”, “all permutations” → think symmetry.

If the expression is a sum of products or “taken k at a time” → think coefficients / combinatorics.

If denominators complicate sums → try reciprocal / substitution.

If quantifiers over integers or “divisible by” → go modular.

If the problem asks a limit/derivative/integral with symmetry → test substitution/x↦1−x or parity transforms.

If a process repeats → seek invariant or monovariant.

If terms cancel in successive indices → attempt to telescope.

