You present the seed in words before you write a line of algebra.

You show the brute impulse and explain why it would be poor or costly.

You give the elegant pivot conceptually, then show a short, minimal calculation that finishes the problem.

You list the pitfalls and the quick checks that detect them.

You give one connection or variant that places the trick in a family.

You finish with a crisp takeaway — the small idea the reader must carry forward.

Final practical checklist (to use before every problem)
Read title & chapter — ask: why is it here?

Say the seed aloud in one sentence. If you cannot, scan hints/small cases.

Spend 60–90 seconds probing (small n, special substitutions).

If pivot emerges → write 2–4 line elegant solution + 1-line exam form.

If no pivot → do a controlled brute step (2–3 lines) to generate more insight.

Add one connection and one “exam note”.

