This white paper codifies a philosophy of mathematical and physical problem solving centered on a compact, repeatable cognitive routine: identify the seed (the small, often-hidden structural idea), recognise the brute/naïve impulse and its cost, find the elegant pivot (a transformation or viewpoint that collapses complexity), guard against pitfalls, connect the instance to wider patterns, and distil a single takeaway. Implemented as a disciplined practice — daily commentaries, peer review, a certification pipeline, and a pedagogical curriculum — this approach trains students to think like examiners and solvers rather than rote technicians. The paper describes the theory, explicit templates, training regimen, evaluation metrics, and operational plan for scaling the movement to cohorts and certified teachers.

1. The core idea: seed → pivot as the unit of thought
Mathematical problems are engineered: an examiner hides a small structural idea (the seed) inside a wrapper (notation, computation, distracting symmetry). The solver’s job is not first to compute, but to decode — find the seed — then select the elegant path (pivot) that makes the seed decisive. Brute force is only a diagnostic tool and should be used minimally. Over time, repeatedly locating seeds and pivots becomes an internalized reflex — the hallmark of mathematical maturity.

Key properties of the seed→pivot unit:

Locality: seed is small (one observation, one invariant, one substitution).

Generativity: pivot generalises (solves a family of instances).

Economy: pivot reduces degrees of freedom, often to a known identity or canonical step.

Testability: small-n cases validate the pivot quickly.

2. The Six-Point Commentary: a reproducible unit
To teach and assess this habit, we make the cognitive routine explicit as a six-part commentary template that students write for each problem:

Seed (author’s intent): 1-line identification of the structural clue.

Brute path / First impulse: the natural naïve attempt and why it is costly.

Elegant pivot: the core idea that collapses the problem, with a compact derivation/sketch.

Pitfalls & Distractions: 2–3 common mistakes and quick checks to detect them.

Connections & Generalizations: where the pivot recurs; one variant exercise.

Key Takeaway: one SRS-ready sentence and a 2–3 line “exam note” (concise writeup).

Minor Joshi-tuned augmentations: prefix seed with “author’s intent / chapter link”, include a 1-line “sanity/assumptions” for analysis/ODE/probability problems, and append an “exam note” to translate the commentary into a 2–4 line exam solution.

