4. Pedagogy: drills, curriculum, and coach interventions
Daily micro-practice

Two 45–60 minute drills per day: one Math commentary, one Physics commentary.

Format: Phase A (15–20 min mental seed identification + sketch), Phase B (15–20 min skeleton), Phase C (15–20 min typed LaTeX final).

Weekday home practice: 6 problems/week (3 Math, 3 Physics) — full commentaries.

Weekly & monthly structure

Weekend live sessions: 50 weekends/year, 10 hours/weekend (5 Math, 5 Physics). Each 5-hour day covers: short concept lecture → JEE-level problems → framework application + commentary on one JEE problem and one Olympiad-level problem → key takeaways.

Escalation: months 1–2 guided hinting; months 3–6 scaffold removal and cross-theme seeds; months 6+ live sessions predominantly Olympiad-level.

Curriculum outline (50 sessions / subject)
Five themes × 10 sessions (e.g., Algebra/Foundations, Calculus, Coordinate Geometry, Combinatorics/Probability, Advanced Topics & Synthesis). Each session escalates from core concept → JEE problem → Olympiad variant.

Coach interventions

Early weeks: guided hints inspired by KD Joshi style; mid-phase: critique scaffolding; late-phase: emulate exam conditions (timed, compressed write-ups).

Peer review and mentor review: each commentary is reviewed by certified students, AI assistant, and the mentor.

5. Assessment: rubric, metrics, and certification
Daily rubric (0–10 per commentary) — the concrete scoring system used during review:

Seed identification (max 2 pts)

Brute path clarity (max 1–2 pts)

Elegant pivot clarity and minimal algebra (max 3 pts)

Pitfalls & checks (max 1–1.5 pts)

Connections/generalization (max 1–1.5 pts)

Presentation & takeaway (max 1–1.5 pts)
Physics variant tweaks weight toward assumptions, diagram, limiting cases.

Quality gates & portfolio requirement

Certification requirement: 1000 commentaries per student (500 Math, 500 Physics), each reaching a quality threshold (median score target ≥ 7) and passing peer/mentor review.

Attempts: student may attempt certification twice; final attempt must be after revision period.

Progress metrics (tracked continuously)

Commentary count by student/subject.

Median Phase A time (seed recognition) — goal: reduction over time.

Average rubric score per week — target: ≥7 after month 2.

Revisit success % (re-solve without notes after 2 weeks).

Problem construction ability: count of valid constructed problems per student.

Mock-test integration

Last 3 months: intensive mock-test program replicating exam constraints, testing speed and exam-skeleton execution.

