7. Quality control, ethics, and risks
Quality control

Multi-tier review: AI preliminary checks; peer reviewer; mentor final approval.

Random audits of commentaries and constructed problems.

Maintain a master set of “master commentaries” (10–15 per chapter) to serve as exemplars.

Ethical considerations

Avoid over-reliance on automation. The goal is to teach thinking, not produce answers. Any app or assistance must require students to submit their own draft before seeing automated suggestions.

Risks & mitigations

Risk: Students game the system by producing superficial commentaries.
Mitigation: Peer review + mentor spot-checks + scoring thresholds + re-attempt limits.

Risk: Scaling dilutes quality through under-trained certified teachers.
Mitigation: rigorous teacher-training; small maximum batch sizes (≤35); certification for teachers only after supervised teaching practicum.

Risk: Burnout from high volume.
Mitigation: Emphasize depth; cadence of 45–60 min drills with built-in reflection, and mental health support.

8. Tools & optional app architecture (principled approach)
Role of software

Not as a substitute for cognitive work, but as a mirror and scaffold: student writes commentary; app performs structural checks, highlights missing parts (e.g., no pitfalls listed), and offers a comparative model commentary only after student submission.

Key features

LaTeX templates, submission tracking, rubric-based auto-evaluation, side-by-side model commentary, revision history, analytics dashboard.

Peer review workflow integrated; mentor notifications for low-quality submissions.

Data export for research and book material.

Guardrails

Require students to confirm “I wrote this” and optionally timestamped drafts.

Model commentary shown after initial submission.

Limit the extent of auto-generated text; focus on hints and checks.

