Purpose: Provide a single, operational blueprint that turns individual problem solutions into reusable learning artifacts, high-quality datasets, and teachable curricula. This paper specifies the pedagogy (Six-Point Commentary), the universal archetypes (Seed–Elegance connections), workflows (MVC → Stage-2 pipeline), quality invariants, dataset schema, training regimen, and example commentaries. Use this as the canonical reference for writing the 1,000 commentaries and for building the Advaitian products that follow.

Executive summary
Challenging mathematics problems are not random: they are disguised instances of a small set of deep structural archetypes. Mastery comes from learning to name the seed — the invariant or hidden structure that unlocks an elegant pivot — and from training the habit of checking brute paths, pitfalls and connections.

This white paper defines:

A Six-Point Commentary template that turns every solution into a teaching artifact (Seed, Brute path, Elegant pivot, Pitfalls, Connections, Takeaway).

A taxonomy of 20 Seed–Elegance archetypes grouped into five meta-categories (Structure Recognition; Transformation Thinking; Constraint Exploitation; Counting & Extremization; Meta-Reasoning).

A practical two-stage workflow (MVC → Stage-2) for fast, consistent production.

Quality invariants and a rubric for peer review.

Data schema and tagging conventions to make the corpus a gold dataset usable for AI orchestration, retrieval, and agent training.

Pedagogical program and a road map for producing and using 1,000 commentaries as a curriculum, a dataset, and the seed of a thinking engine.

Two worked examples (polygon AP angles; GP index reconstruction) are used to demonstrate the method and the archetypal reasoning.

1. Motivating principles
Clarity is the primary pedagogical good. Students learn to think, not to memorize. A commentary must teach the insight and why it is the insight.

Small, repeatable patterns scale. A limited set of archetypes explains a broad variety of problems; naming them accelerates recognition.

Teach process, not just answer. The process: generate candidates → filter with domain constraints → select elegant pivot → verify & generalize.

Assets must be reusable. Every commentary must be machine-readable, taggable, and suitable as training data for explainable reasoning systems.

Human + AI co-creation. The corpus should enable human teachers to scale via AI tools (co-pilots, assessment aids) while preserving pedagogy.

2. The Six-Point Commentary (canonical template)
Every final commentary must include these six sections. Use clear, short language; minimal equations in Stage-1; rigorous but concise maths in Stage-2.

SEED — a one-sentence distillation of the hidden meta-pattern (domain-general; reusable).
Goal: immediate recognition; what to look for first.

BRUTE PATH — the mechanical approach a typical student would try.
Goal: honest, diagnostic; show why brute force is natural and where it fails.

ELEGANT PIVOT — the key insight or transformation that makes the solution trivial.
Goal: the “aha” that should feel inevitable in hindsight.

PITFALLS — 3–5 named traps with short checks to avoid them.
Goal: make common student mistakes visible and actionable.

CONNECTIONS — two parts: (A) where this archetype applies elsewhere (in same topic); (B) alternative archetypes that could solve this problem and when they might be preferable.
Goal: strengthen transfer and epistemic humility.

TAKEAWAY — one memorable, actionable principle (domain-general) the student can recall and apply.

Formatting conventions: include ARCHETYPES: tags; Answer: line; short final verification checks (sanity / units / limits). Where helpful, include a tiny diagram or numeric check.

3. The 20 Seed–Elegance archetypes
Below is the canonical taxonomy to be used for tagging and for teaching. Each entry in the corpus should include up to 3 archetype tags: Primary, Secondary, Tertiary.

Category A — Structure Recognition (see the hidden architecture)
Invariance — something conserved; anchor the argument.

Symmetry — reduce degrees of freedom via identical views.

Duality — solve in a dual space and map back.

Hidden Structure (Pattern Recognition) — recognize disguised common templates.

Category B — Transformation Thinking (change representation)
Substitution / Change of Variables — find the right coordinates.

Linearization / Simplification — reduce to linear core.

Normalization / Scaling — remove irrelevant scale.

Translation Between Domains — move to the natural domain (algebra ↔ geometry, discrete ↔ continuous).

Category C — Constraint Exploitation (use the restrictions)
Domain Constraints / Bounds — dismiss algebraic roots violating physical/geometric bounds.

Inequality Constraints — exploit classical inequalities.

Uniqueness / Existence Conditions — necessary/sufficient analysis.

Extremal Principles — optimization and variational reasoning.

Category D — Counting & Extremization (structure the chaos)
Combinatorial Principles — bijections, inclusion–exclusion, generating functions.

Parity / Modularity — residues simplify cases.

Bijection / Correspondence — map counts to easier counts.

Category E — Meta-Reasoning (think about the problem)
Reverse Engineering — work backwards from given values/answers.

Degrees of Freedom Analysis — count constraints vs variables.

Recursion / Induction — stepwise solution building.

Pivoting / Elimination — remove variables one by one.

Analogy / Transfer — match to a known solved structure.

(Optional additions: Probabilistic / Expectation Thinking; Constructive Existence — can be included as explicit items if needed.)

4. The two-stage production workflow (MVC → Stage-2)
Stage-1: MVC (Minimum Viable Commentary)
Purpose: fast conversational reasoning capture.
Inputs: Problem statement + a short conversational MVC written by the human (30–90s mental output). MVC must include: seed intuition, brute-force space, candidate pivot idea (no equations).
AI/Human role: Validate or refine the MVC conversationally. Only proceed to Stage-2 when MVC is accepted.

Stage-1 output: Your MVC is solid. Ready for Stage 2. or a refined MVC (still conversational, crisp).

Rationale: prevents premature formalization, preserves pedagogy, reduces wasted formal work.

Stage-2: Formalization (Gold commentary)
Purpose: produce the final 6-point commentary, rigorous and polished. Include: precise seed, detailed brute path, concise pivot with math, 3–5 pitfalls (with quick checks), connections (A & B), takeaway. Tag archetypes and include Answer: and Check: lines. Export in LaTeX / JSON for dataset ingestion.

Stage-2 output format: LaTeX file + JSON metadata:

{
 "problem_id":"math_001",
 "title":"Polygon AP angles",
 "archtypes":["Invariance","DomainConstraint"],
 "seed":"Intersection of definitions: AP sum vs polygon sum",
 "brute":"...",
 "pivot":"Domain constraint: a_n < 180°",
 "pitfalls":["Double-root trap","Formula confusion","Ignoring last term"],
 "connections":["Physics time-root negative","Inequalities","Exterior-angle check"],
 "takeaway":"Algebra generates candidates; geometry selects the winner",
 "answer":"n=9",
 "difficulty":"easy-medium",
 "sources":["Joshi_Ch2_P1"]
}
5. Quality invariants & rubric
Each commentary must satisfy the six quality invariants. Authors or reviewers score each item (1–5). Use these thresholds to accept a commentary into the canonical corpus.

Clarity — no ambiguity or jargon (score ≥ 4).

Depth — reveals structure beyond mechanics (score ≥ 4).

Generality — principle transfers to other problems (score ≥ 3).

Precision — mathematically correct & compact (score ≥ 4).

Memorability — takeaway is concise & sticky (score ≥ 4).

Reusability — tags & metadata present; suitable for dataset (score ≥ 4).

Peer review process: two independent reviewers + auto check for math errors (basic verification scripts). If reviewer scores differ by > 2 in any invariant, send to senior editor (you).

6. Tagging & dataset schema (gold dataset engineering)
Metadata fields (minimum)
problem_id, source, authors, date, difficulty, topics (algebra, geometry, combinatorics), archetypes (list), seed, pivot_keywords, pitfalls_list, connections_list, takeaway, final_answer, latex_text, json_equations, time_log (Phase A/B/C).

Archetype tagging
Use canonical codes (e.g., A_INVAR, B_SUBST, C_DOMAIN). Tag primary+secondary. This enables retrieval by method.

Dataset uses
Train explainable reasoning agents (thinking-bot).

Build retrieval augmentation for prompts (fetch commentaries with same archetype & difficulty).

Create assessment rubrics for students (diagnose mistakes via pitfall matching).

Provenance & licensing
Each record must include source_ref and rights. Prefer permissive license for internal use; commercial licensing for third parties.

