Include live oral spot checks for pivot articulation in <5 minutes.

8. Examples (worked, condensed)
Example 1 — Polygon with AP interior angles
(Condensed Stage-2 commentary summary)

Seed: Intersection of definitions — algebraic AP sum vs geometric polygon sum.

Brute path: Equate AP sum to (n−2)×180°, produce quadratic → roots n=9,16.

Elegant pivot: Domain constraint — convex polygon interior angle < 180°, aₙ = 120 + (n−1)×5 < 180°, so n=16 invalid (a₁₆=195°) → answer n=9.

Pitfalls: Double-root acceptance; mixing interior & exterior sums; ignoring last term.

Connections: Negative kinematic root filtering; exterior-angle quick check.

Takeaway: Algebra produces candidates; domain constraints select the real solutions.

(Include Answer: n = 9, quick numeric check.)

Example 2 — GP sample reconstruction (27,8,12 at p,q,r)
Seed: Reverse engineering — reconstruct GP from samples; look at ratios.

Brute path: Trial indices leads to random search.

Elegant pivot: Use ratios: 8/27 = (2/3)³ ⇒ q−p = 3 if R=2/3; 12/8 = 3/2 = (2/3)^(−1) ⇒ r−q = −1 ⇒ indices consistent with p,q,r = p, p+3, p+2. One set: (1,4,3).

Pitfalls: Consecutive-index assumption; notation confusion between index r and ratio r.

Connections: Logarithmic linearization converts GP → AP; system identification analogues.

Takeaway: When the answer/data is given, decode the data structure before algebra.

